<TITLE>City of Greeley launches water budget program, setting personalized budgets for every Greeley household</TITLE>


<TEXT>
For the first time in <TIMEX3 tid="t1" type="DURATION" value="P100Y">100 years</TIMEX3>, Greeley residents may have the freedom <TIMEX3 tid="t2" type="DATE" value="2017">this year</TIMEX3> to <EVENT eid="e1" class="OCCURRENCE">water</EVENT> their lawns whenever they <EVENT eid="e2" class="OCCURRENCE">want</EVENT>. 
 
Since <TIMEX3 tid="t3" type="DATE" value="1907">1907</TIMEX3>, residents have <EVENT eid="e3" class="REPORTING">faced</EVENT> limits on watering days  usually <TIMEX3 tid="t4" type="DURATION" value="PXD">every other day</TIMEX3>  during <TIMEX3 tid="t5" type="DURATION" value="PXM">warmer months</TIMEX3>. Thanks to an overhauled water budget system , residents may soon have the power to <EVENT eid="e4" class="OCCURRENCE">pick</EVENT> their days  any <TIMEX3 tid="t6" type="DURATION" value="PXD">days</TIMEX3>; all <TIMEX3 tid="t7" type="DURATION" value="PXD">days</TIMEX3>  so long as they stay within their budget. 
 
The Greeley water and sewer board <EVENT eid="e5" class="ASPECTUAL">approved lifting</EVENT> the <EVENT eid="e6" class="OCCURRENCE">restrictions</EVENT>, but the city council will have to <EVENT eid="e7" class="OCCURRENCE">give</EVENT> final approval  likely <TIMEX3 tid="t8" type="DATE" value="2017-02">next month</TIMEX3>. 
 
Its pretty simple, <EVENT eid="e8" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT> Harold Evans, chairman of the citys water and sewer board. If Im going to <EVENT eid="e9" class="REPORTING">say</EVENT> you <EVENT eid="e10" class="STATE">have</EVENT> a budget, we <EVENT eid="e11" class="I_STATE">shouldnt tell</EVENT> you what days you should water. 
 
Watering freedom would <EVENT eid="e12" class="OCCURRENCE">run</EVENT> from <TIMEX3 tid="t9" type="DATE" value="2017-04-01">April 1</TIMEX3> through <TIMEX3 tid="t10" type="DATE" value="2017-10-31">Oct. 31</TIMEX3>, and city officials would <EVENT eid="e13" class="OCCURRENCE">take</EVENT> a look at the results before <EVENT eid="e14" class="OCCURRENCE">deciding</EVENT> whether to <EVENT eid="e15" class="OCCURRENCE">keep</EVENT> it <EVENT eid="e16" class="OCCURRENCE">going</EVENT> in <TIMEX3 tid="t11" type="DATE" value="2018">2018</TIMEX3>. The water budget, however, is here to say. 
 
The water budget and watering day freedom  would <EVENT eid="e17" class="OCCURRENCE">apply</EVENT> only to residential, single-family homes. Even then, the city will <EVENT eid="e18" class="I_ACTION">restrict watering</EVENT> between <TIMEX3 tid="t12" type="TIME" value="2017-01-29T12:00">noon-5</TIMEX3> p.m. Businesses and other commercial property will <EVENT eid="e19" class="OCCURRENCE">maintain</EVENT> the same water rate structure as theyve <EVENT eid="e20" class="STATE">had</EVENT> in <TIMEX3 tid="t13" type="DATE" value="PAST_REF">the past</TIMEX3>. 
 
Single-family homes account for nearly half of the citys overall water usage, <EVENT eid="e21" class="OCCURRENCE">making</EVENT> that category ripe for change. 
 
Evans <EVENT eid="e22" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT> the budget, which will <EVENT eid="e23" class="OCCURRENCE">take</EVENT> effect <TIMEX3 tid="t14" type="DATE" value="2017-01-25">Wednesday</TIMEX3>, is more than <TIMEX3 tid="t15" type="DURATION" value="P1E">a decade</TIMEX3> in the <EVENT eid="e24" class="OCCURRENCE">making</EVENT>, as city officials <EVENT eid="e25" class="I_ACTION">sought</EVENT> to <EVENT eid="e26" class="OCCURRENCE">stave</EVENT> off the effects of a drought like the one the state <EVENT eid="e27" class="OCCURRENCE">saw</EVENT> in early <TIMEX3 tid="t16" type="DATE" value="200X">2000s</TIMEX3> . 
 
<EVENT eid="e28" class="OCCURRENCE">Coming</EVENT> to consensus <EVENT eid="e29" class="OCCURRENCE">took</EVENT> a lot of work, as did <EVENT eid="e30" class="OCCURRENCE">developing</EVENT> the budget for every household. 
 
Greeley staffers <EVENT eid="e31" class="OCCURRENCE">mapped</EVENT> every plot of land in Greeley to <EVENT eid="e32" class="OCCURRENCE">calculate</EVENT> the amount of irrigable area  basically any property you have outside of your roof, sidewalk and driveway. They <EVENT eid="e33" class="REPORTING">used</EVENT> that area, <EVENT eid="e34" class="OCCURRENCE">combined</EVENT> it with an assumption that every inch of that area is <EVENT eid="e35" class="OCCURRENCE">planted</EVENT> with bluegrass, and <EVENT eid="e36" class="OCCURRENCE">came</EVENT> up with a formula that <EVENT eid="e37" class="OCCURRENCE">spits</EVENT> out enough water to <EVENT eid="e38" class="OCCURRENCE">take</EVENT> care of all of that. 
 
I <EVENT eid="e39" class="I_STATE">think</EVENT> its the core of what the water budget is all about, City Manager Roy Otto <EVENT eid="e40" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT>, referencing the personalized water budget. 
 
Inside, the city will budget 55 gallons per person per <TIMEX3 tid="t17" type="DURATION" value="PXD">day</TIMEX3>, with the assumption that there are three people in every household. (Call the city if you have a larger family). 
 
City officials <EVENT eid="e41" class="REPORTING">say</EVENT> the budget should <EVENT eid="e42" class="OCCURRENCE">provide</EVENT> more than enough water for most residents. In <EVENT eid="e43" class="OCCURRENCE">testing</EVENT> the program with 16,700 households, the city <EVENT eid="e44" class="OCCURRENCE">found</EVENT> 83 percent of folks <EVENT eid="e45" class="OCCURRENCE">stayed</EVENT> within budget. 
 
If you <EVENT eid="e46" class="OCCURRENCE">dont</EVENT>, well, youll get <EVENT eid="e47" class="OCCURRENCE">charged</EVENT> more. <TIMEX3 tid="t18" type="DATE" value="2017">This years</TIMEX3> base rate is $3.97 per 1,000 gallons, which is actually cheaper than what folks <EVENT eid="e48" class="OCCURRENCE">paid</EVENT> <TIMEX3 tid="t19" type="DATE" value="2016">last year</TIMEX3>. 
 
If you <EVENT eid="e49" class="OCCURRENCE">use</EVENT> up to 130 percent more than your budget, youll pay $4.85 per gallon for anything over your budget. The rates <EVENT eid="e50" class="OCCURRENCE">go</EVENT> up to $6.62 and then $8.82 per 1,000 gallons from there. Just 4 percent of the pilot group of 16,700 households <EVENT eid="e51" class="OCCURRENCE">went</EVENT> that far over their budget. 
 
We <EVENT eid="e52" class="I_STATE">think</EVENT> weve <EVENT eid="e53" class="OCCURRENCE">developed</EVENT> a program that will <EVENT eid="e54" class="I_ACTION">reward</EVENT> efficiency, and yet it will also <EVENT eid="e55" class="ASPECTUAL">provide</EVENT> an incentive for people who are over-watering to <EVENT eid="e56" class="OCCURRENCE">cut</EVENT> back, Evans <EVENT eid="e57" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT>. 
 
For <TIMEX3 tid="t20" type="DATE" value="PRESENT_REF">now</TIMEX3>, the changes <EVENT eid="e58" class="STATE">wont apply</EVENT> to businesses or other commercial property. Thats a little more tricky. 
 
A typical, tiered-rate structure would have been easier. That would <EVENT eid="e59" class="OCCURRENCE">involve</EVENT> one rate for a certain amount of water, and higher rates for anything above that. 
 
Fort Collins has one, and such a structure can <EVENT eid="e60" class="OCCURRENCE">punish</EVENT> homeowners with a larger lot even if those homeowners practice water conservation. 
 
Without that work <EVENT eid="e61" class="OCCURRENCE">done</EVENT> by the staff, we would have arbitrarily <EVENT eid="e62" class="OCCURRENCE">penalized</EVENT> people for being efficient with their water just for <EVENT eid="e63" class="OCCURRENCE">having</EVENT> a larger lot, Otto <EVENT eid="e64" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT>. 
 
City officials <EVENT eid="e65" class="OCCURRENCE">spent</EVENT> so much time <EVENT eid="e66" class="I_ACTION">studying</EVENT> the outdoor water use because they <EVENT eid="e67" class="OCCURRENCE">say</EVENT> its the area with the most potential for savings. In some months  particularly <TIMEX3 tid="t21" type="DATE" value="2017-04">April</TIMEX3> and <TIMEX3 tid="t22" type="DATE" value="2017-10">October</TIMEX3>, when people run their sprinklers more than necessary  the city as a whole could <EVENT eid="e68" class="OCCURRENCE">cut</EVENT> water usage by half or more, according to city data. 
 
As Greeley <EVENT eid="e69" class="OCCURRENCE">grows</EVENT> toward 250,000 people by <TIMEX3 tid="t23" type="DATE" value="2060">2060</TIMEX3>, <EVENT eid="e70" class="OCCURRENCE">getting</EVENT> folks in the habit of <EVENT eid="e71" class="OCCURRENCE">thinking</EVENT> about water conservation will be key, Evans <EVENT eid="e72" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT>. 
 
Theres a finite supply of water in Colorado, Evans <EVENT eid="e73" class="REPORTING">said</EVENT>. Weve <EVENT eid="e74" class="REPORTING">got</EVENT> to be more efficient. 
 
